WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.350
JAMES: So I'm super excited
to have Vicki Abeles-- did

00:00:06.350 --> 00:00:07.070
I get it right?

00:00:07.070 --> 00:00:07.240
VICKI ABELES: Yes.

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:07.650
JAMES: Close?

00:00:07.650 --> 00:00:08.774
VICKI ABELES: Close enough.

00:00:08.774 --> 00:00:11.140
JAMES: Excellent, yes--
uh-oh, close enough--

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:12.240
to have Vicki here.

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:13.150
She's an inspiration.

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:15.340
She began her career as
a Wall Street attorney

00:00:15.340 --> 00:00:18.140
and turned filmmaker
in 2007 when

00:00:18.140 --> 00:00:20.490
she co-directed the
award winning documentary

00:00:20.490 --> 00:00:21.240
"Race to Nowhere."

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:23.114
Which is more than a
film, it's more a phrase

00:00:23.114 --> 00:00:25.730
now used by parents--
a rallying cry.

00:00:25.730 --> 00:00:28.720
It's a vivid portrayal of
the pressure cooker culture

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:31.020
dominating American schools,
which you got a taste

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:32.409
of in the videos we showed.

00:00:32.409 --> 00:00:34.150
So Vicki showcased
"Race to Nowhere"

00:00:34.150 --> 00:00:37.579
in more than 7,000 community
sponsored screenings--

00:00:37.579 --> 00:00:39.370
including multiple
showings at Google years

00:00:39.370 --> 00:00:41.830
ago-- to millions of
viewers around the globe.

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:44.830
She is also the
author of a book.

00:00:44.830 --> 00:00:45.584
There it is.

00:00:45.584 --> 00:00:48.000
After you read this book it
will be full of post-it notes,

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.090
I guarantee you.

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:52.800
She's an-- amazing book,
"Beyond Measure," which is also

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:55.420
a documentary of the same name.

00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:57.080
Which builds on
"Race to Nowhere,"

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:58.669
by looking at
practical solutions

00:00:58.669 --> 00:01:00.960
that you can take in your
homes, classrooms, and school

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:01.600
districts.

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.650
Starting tomorrow or even today.

00:01:03.650 --> 00:01:06.520
So Vicki's films and books were
a wake up call in our family

00:01:06.520 --> 00:01:10.414
and in our district where the
film was shown-- both films.

00:01:10.414 --> 00:01:12.580
And it served as a rallying
cry to make a difference

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:15.625
in the lives of our children and
the students of our community.

00:01:15.625 --> 00:01:18.440
So Vicki, welcome to Google.

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:20.020
VICKI ABELES: Thank you.

00:01:20.020 --> 00:01:22.417
JAMES: So I'm going to let
you do most of the talking.

00:01:22.417 --> 00:01:25.000
And in a little bit we're going
to introduce a special Googler

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:25.660
to join us.

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:27.930
But I want to start with
the thought of producing

00:01:27.930 --> 00:01:30.370
not one film but two.

00:01:30.370 --> 00:01:32.260
And authoring a book
is absolutely daunting.

00:01:32.260 --> 00:01:34.030
Doing any one of those
three is daunting.

00:01:34.030 --> 00:01:35.590
So talk about the
moment when you

00:01:35.590 --> 00:01:39.350
were inspired to devote so
much energy to this task.

00:01:39.350 --> 00:01:40.530
VICKI ABELES: Sure.

00:01:40.530 --> 00:01:42.950
So about 10 years
ago my daughters

00:01:42.950 --> 00:01:46.220
were in middle school,
fifth and seventh grade.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:50.950
And as a parent I started to
see the pressures and the toll

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:53.410
that school was taking
on them and our family.

00:01:53.410 --> 00:01:56.430
I saw two young girls
who went from being

00:01:56.430 --> 00:02:00.410
happy, confident girls
who loved school.

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:01.400
To losing sleep.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:02.650
To becoming anxious.

00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:05.280
To waking up in panic attacks
during the middle of the night

00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:07.510
about a test the next day.

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:10.949
And I started to wonder if
this was just my family.

00:02:10.949 --> 00:02:14.130
So I started speaking to
families in my community.

00:02:14.130 --> 00:02:18.570
And then eventually to families,
educators, health professionals

00:02:18.570 --> 00:02:20.030
across the country.

00:02:20.030 --> 00:02:22.050
And what I discovered
was an epidemic

00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:26.270
of unhealthy, unprepared,
disengaged young people.

00:02:26.270 --> 00:02:28.850
And then about six
months into my research

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:31.195
a young girl, 13
years old-- same age

00:02:31.195 --> 00:02:36.180
as my oldest daughter-- took her
life after failing a math test.

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:39.950
And it was in that moment that
I knew I had to do something.

00:02:39.950 --> 00:02:42.970
And so I thought to myself,
what if we could do something

00:02:42.970 --> 00:02:47.510
to really listen to our
kids, give our kids a voice?

00:02:47.510 --> 00:02:49.890
And those questions
are what ultimately

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:52.214
lead to "Race to Nowhere."

00:02:52.214 --> 00:02:53.130
JAMES: That's amazing.

00:02:53.130 --> 00:02:54.990
I can't think of
anything more motivating,

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:58.334
and I wish that's not what
it took to motivate change.

00:02:58.334 --> 00:03:00.750
That kind of leads into the
second question, which is fear

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:01.980
is a powerful
motivator-- although we

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:03.530
spoke at lunch how
this really should

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:05.220
be about inspiring people.

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:07.160
So should parents be
scared about the health

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:09.740
of their children or see
a tremendous opportunity

00:03:09.740 --> 00:03:10.940
to do something much better?

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:14.390
And if so, why is
either the case?

00:03:14.390 --> 00:03:16.750
VICKI ABELES: So I don't
want to be an alarmist.

00:03:16.750 --> 00:03:19.180
But here is what the data shows.

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:22.060
One in three students reported
to the American Psychological

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:24.785
Association that
they are stressed

00:03:24.785 --> 00:03:28.600
and that that stress is
leading them to depression.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:32.570
The number one source of the
stress cited by 83% of students

00:03:32.570 --> 00:03:34.450
was school.

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:37.420
The CDC reports that the
majority of teenagers

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:40.480
in this country get two hours
less of sleep each night

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:41.950
than what's recommended.

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:45.520
And then in a recent survey that
we conducted in collaboration

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:48.400
with a pediatrician from St.
Louis at a local Bay Area

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:49.550
high school.

00:03:49.550 --> 00:03:52.910
What we discovered
was really concerning.

00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:55.590
We did a survey about the
wellness of that community.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.280
Community surveying middle
class families, about

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:00.280
2000 high school students.

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:03.220
More than 50% of
those students we're

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:06.160
showing signs of moderate
to severe depression.

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:07.750
More than 50%.

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:11.310
I think what we have, James,
is a public health crisis.

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:14.870
On a scale that we have
yet to fully recognize.

00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:17.779
And at the same time I think
that we need to use that data

00:04:17.779 --> 00:04:20.570
and what we know-- even
annecdotatelly-- in our homes,

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:24.130
in our classrooms, in our
communities, to inspire action.

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:26.360
And just a quick
example-- you may

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:28.670
be familiar with this-- but
the Burbank school district

00:04:28.670 --> 00:04:30.650
has taken these
issues seriously.

00:04:30.650 --> 00:04:32.930
They've created a
wellness task force.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.690
They now have a wellness center
at one of their high schools.

00:04:35.690 --> 00:04:38.225
They adopted a suicide
prevention policy

00:04:38.225 --> 00:04:39.600
in their district,
which involved

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:43.030
professional development for
all professionals ranging

00:04:43.030 --> 00:04:45.805
from teachers to
administer to janitors.

00:04:45.805 --> 00:04:48.430
And they are also addressing the
source of the unhealthy stress

00:04:48.430 --> 00:04:49.280
in our kids lives.

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:52.640
Ranging from homework to AP
courses to too much testing.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:55.280
So I'm really inspired by that
story and there are stories

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:55.781
like that.

00:04:55.781 --> 00:04:57.571
Which you knew, we
write about in our book.

00:04:57.571 --> 00:04:59.900
JAMES: Yes, well I want to
switch around a little bit

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:01.441
and talk about
wellness for a second.

00:05:01.441 --> 00:05:05.000
So mindfulness is something
that has been taught

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.140
to thousands of Googlers.

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:10.120
As one of the
training programs we

00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:12.980
get to take, addressing
stress is one of the things

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:14.800
we think about-- it's
part of our culture.

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:16.550
How have some of the
districts that you've

00:05:16.550 --> 00:05:19.910
spoken to taken practical
steps on addressing stress?

00:05:19.910 --> 00:05:22.330
VICKI ABELES: So we see a
number of districts and schools

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:25.370
and even teachers who are
adopting mindfulness programs.

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:26.679
Adding Yoga to the school day.

00:05:26.679 --> 00:05:28.220
And I think that's
terrific and there

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:30.870
is great research to support
the benefits of that.

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:33.570
At the same time,
I am an advocate

00:05:33.570 --> 00:05:35.920
for getting to the source
of the unhealthy stress.

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:39.380
And I think, unfortunately,
too many of our kids

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:41.860
are suffering from a
system and a culture that

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:46.280
values business-- and oftentimes
that means too much homework.

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:50.790
That values constant measurement
and the arms race to college.

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:53.800
And I think that it's really
incumbent upon all of us

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:57.150
as people who care for
students, for children,

00:05:57.150 --> 00:05:59.380
to address those
unhealthy stressors.

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:02.460
And at the same time to add
programs like mindfulness.

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:05.580
JAMES: So that leads to the next
thought I have-- is all right,

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:10.250
so part of this is students
get caught up in the arms race

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:11.560
with their peers.

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:13.750
Feeling like it's a badge
of honor to lose sleep

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:15.940
and to take 10 AP classes.

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:18.640
Parents get terrified
about their kids

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:20.000
getting into the right school.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.440
And everyone seems to be
trapped in this cycle.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:24.840
So how do you
respond to this fear

00:06:24.840 --> 00:06:27.110
of being disadvantaged
if you're the first one

00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:29.100
to try to address this problem.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:31.885
VICKI ABELES: Right, so I think
that's an excellent point,

00:06:31.885 --> 00:06:35.660
is that no one really wants to
step off the treadmill first.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:37.650
But we're at Goggle
here today and so

00:06:37.650 --> 00:06:39.810
let's think about the
things that make people

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:41.350
at Google successful, right?

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:42.990
I imagine many people
at this company

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:45.189
are successful because
they're creative,

00:06:45.189 --> 00:06:46.980
because they're
self-starters, because they

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:48.600
know how to get things done.

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:51.240
And unfortunately
our schools today

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:54.060
are set up in ways that our
kids spend most of their days

00:06:54.060 --> 00:06:57.730
sitting in rows, consuming
information and regurgitating

00:06:57.730 --> 00:06:58.230
it.

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:00.470
That's what we value in
many of our schools today.

00:07:00.470 --> 00:07:03.800
And unfortunately we crowd
out the opportunity for them

00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:06.290
to develop the very skill
that are going to serve them,

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:10.220
not just in college and their
future employment, but in life.

00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:12.700
And so, you know, what
I find really inspiring

00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:15.660
are those schools that we
have followed these last three

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:18.050
years in the film "Beyond
Measure" and in the book,

00:07:18.050 --> 00:07:19.900
that are taking
steps to re-imagine

00:07:19.900 --> 00:07:22.475
what's possible in our school.

00:07:22.475 --> 00:07:24.850
And I think that's the question
we need to ask ourselves.

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:29.090
What if we design schools in a
way that prioritized wellness

00:07:29.090 --> 00:07:30.020
and learning?

00:07:30.020 --> 00:07:33.350
JAMES: So that in the movie
you have some amazing examples

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:36.810
of innovation around schools
changing-- charter schools,

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:38.489
public schools,
that didn't really

00:07:38.489 --> 00:07:40.030
seem to be the
factors-- just schools

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:42.250
that took that first step,
not just the individual

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:45.350
but-- what are some of the most
inspiring examples of schools

00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:48.000
that have taken that leap of
faith and seen it at least

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.060
head the right direction.

00:07:49.060 --> 00:07:51.420
VICKI ABELES: Right, so
we've visited schools that

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:53.380
are taking steps big and small.

00:07:53.380 --> 00:07:55.920
What I want to
highlight is the process

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:58.279
of change, the process that
creates change is really

00:07:58.279 --> 00:07:59.570
what we want to be focusing on.

00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:01.230
And it's critical
that that process

00:08:01.230 --> 00:08:04.260
include all of the stake
holders in a community.

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:06.500
Ranging from students--
students need

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.850
to be an important voice
in these conversations,

00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:12.180
they need to inform the design
or the redesign of the school.

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:15.360
In fact, in all of the schools
that we feature in our new film

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:18.670
students were an integral
part of the design process.

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:21.020
You need to engage the
superintendents, the community

00:08:21.020 --> 00:08:21.880
members.

00:08:21.880 --> 00:08:25.090
I think everybody needs to be
a part of this conversation.

00:08:25.090 --> 00:08:28.540
There is no greater resource
and important issue,

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:31.830
I think, than addressing
the well-being of our kids

00:08:31.830 --> 00:08:33.780
and their preparation
for their future.

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:36.899
JAMES: So what have you
learned to help students break

00:08:36.899 --> 00:08:38.940
this cycle even if their
parents are pushing them

00:08:38.940 --> 00:08:40.731
and even if the districts
are pushing them.

00:08:40.731 --> 00:08:43.320
And I think when we get to Ken
that there's a great example

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:44.000
of that locally.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.230
But where they get into the
idea that this studying late

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.032
at night and even
pretending to go

00:08:50.032 --> 00:08:51.990
to sleep-- as you wrote
about-- and having wake

00:08:51.990 --> 00:08:53.310
up in the middle of the
night doing homework

00:08:53.310 --> 00:08:54.976
when their parents
think they're asleep.

00:08:54.976 --> 00:08:57.554
What are some of the ways
to have students believe

00:08:57.554 --> 00:08:58.720
it's in their best interest?

00:08:58.720 --> 00:08:59.940
VICKI ABELES: Well,
so one of the ways

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:02.280
to have them believe it's
in their best interest is

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:03.850
to tell them stories
of people who

00:09:03.850 --> 00:09:06.179
have taken alternative paths.

00:09:06.179 --> 00:09:07.720
To really convince
them that it's not

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:10.267
the name of the college
that one attends that

00:09:10.267 --> 00:09:11.600
determines your success in life.

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:15.760
And in fact, what colleges,
what employers are looking for

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:17.290
are people who are passionate.

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:18.373
People who are interested.

00:09:18.373 --> 00:09:20.630
People who want to
contribute something

00:09:20.630 --> 00:09:22.080
positive to the world.

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:25.539
That being said, you know, I
think there's a lot of things

00:09:25.539 --> 00:09:27.705
that individuals can do in
their home-- both parents

00:09:27.705 --> 00:09:28.540
and students.

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:32.460
You know, from modeling balance
as parents for our children.

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:35.520
To encouraging our children
to not over schedule

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:38.900
both academically and in
terms of extracurriculars.

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:41.809
But I also think that puts a
lot of burden on individuals.

00:09:41.809 --> 00:09:43.350
And what I want to
say to you, James,

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:47.040
is that I think the individuals
are responding right now

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:49.130
to the culture
that exists, right?

00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:52.000
And if you are a parent
with a child in school,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:53.570
school is the culture.

00:09:53.570 --> 00:09:57.310
And that culture really impacts
your family and your student.

00:09:57.310 --> 00:09:59.810
And so that's why I'm a big
advocate for a school change

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:00.490
as well.

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:02.440
I think that we need
to move away from what

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:03.740
has become a blame game.

00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:06.980
Of blaming college admissions,
of blaming helicopter parents

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:08.625
and say, the individuals
are responding

00:10:08.625 --> 00:10:10.440
to the system and the culture.

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:12.010
And we all make up that culture.

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:14.980
And what we're trying to
do is to empower people

00:10:14.980 --> 00:10:16.150
to change that culture.

00:10:16.150 --> 00:10:18.050
And that takes a
different mindset

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:19.259
about the things that matter.

00:10:19.259 --> 00:10:21.050
JAMES: So that kind of
leads to-- if you're

00:10:21.050 --> 00:10:22.722
trying to implement
any kind of change,

00:10:22.722 --> 00:10:24.180
if you're trying
to sell something,

00:10:24.180 --> 00:10:25.680
you're going to run
into objections.

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:28.370
People are going to come up
with all kinds of reasons

00:10:28.370 --> 00:10:29.360
not to do things.

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:32.890
It's human nature to
be static in some ways.

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:35.540
So what are some of the
most common objections

00:10:35.540 --> 00:10:37.420
you hear, that you
expect to hear,

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:40.000
and how do you counter
those objections.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.920
VICKI ABELES: So I think the
most common objection to things

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:45.230
like reducing the
number of AP courses

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:47.150
or reducing the
amount of homework

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:50.710
is our kids won't be prepared
for what's coming next.

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:52.870
And the reality is
research is very clear

00:10:52.870 --> 00:10:56.640
that the best way to prepare
people for bad situations--

00:10:56.640 --> 00:10:58.770
let's just say high
school homework-- is

00:10:58.770 --> 00:11:02.170
to have lots of good
experience along the way.

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:04.060
But the other argument
that I'll make,

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:08.660
James, is that we know that our
kids are incredibly unhealthy.

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:11.860
They're sleep deprived, they're
anxious, they're depressed.

00:11:11.860 --> 00:11:15.820
They're contemplating
suicide at increasing rates.

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:19.160
And at the same time we
hear from college professors

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:21.220
and from employers
that they're showing up

00:11:21.220 --> 00:11:24.260
unprepared for the kind
of thinking and problem

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:25.330
solving that's needed.

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:28.140
So I don't really think
there is a reason for us not

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:28.980
to make the change.

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:31.820
Oftentimes, I think what
keeps us stuck in the status

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:34.690
quo is the mindset
that school is best

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:37.150
done as it's always done.

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:38.780
And it's incredibly--
you know, there

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:41.440
are a lot of stake holders
that need to come to the table

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:43.920
in order to make the changes.

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:46.950
JAMES: So before we bring
our next member of the panel

00:11:46.950 --> 00:11:48.030
up here.

00:11:48.030 --> 00:11:50.370
I want to finish the
questions directly to you

00:11:50.370 --> 00:11:53.636
about the recommend-- you in the
book in a very practical way.

00:11:53.636 --> 00:11:54.260
Which is great.

00:11:54.260 --> 00:11:55.400
I think it's part of
the reason I think

00:11:55.400 --> 00:11:56.880
you went from "Race to
Nowhere" to "Beyond Measure"

00:11:56.880 --> 00:11:58.500
to give people a
sense of what to do.

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:00.400
So of the many
suggestions you make

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:03.020
at the end of the book, what
are a couple that you would--

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:04.090
for the people in
the Live stream,

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:06.260
here in the audience, who
watch this later on YouTube--

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:07.790
what are some steps
that they can take

00:12:07.790 --> 00:12:10.456
starting tomorrow that you think
are the most practical, to just

00:12:10.456 --> 00:12:11.120
get started.

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:14.000
VICKI ABELES: OK, so I've got
a long winded answer to that.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.380
So big picture in our
schools, I think that we

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:18.100
need to consider three things.

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:19.430
We need to prioritize wellness.

00:12:19.430 --> 00:12:22.050
And that means addressing
unhealthy stressors.

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:24.900
We need to recalibrate the way
time is spent in our schools

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:26.870
around a whole new
set of priorities.

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:30.550
And we need to transform
learning in our schools.

00:12:30.550 --> 00:12:34.660
And each of us, parents,
educators, concerned citizens,

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:39.010
need to play a role in the
advocacy to make that happen.

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:40.700
As far as at the
individual level,

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:43.470
I just want to share a quote
from the film "Beyond Measure."

00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:46.140
Sir Ken Robinson-- I
assume you know who he is--

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:48.870
says at the very end of the
film, if you're a teacher

00:12:48.870 --> 00:12:50.800
and you change what you
do in your classroom

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.650
you have to changed
the education system

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:54.320
for the students in your class.

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:56.644
Now, I think that's a
really empowering thought.

00:12:56.644 --> 00:12:58.060
As you know from
reading the book,

00:12:58.060 --> 00:12:59.670
we share the story
of Mike Miller,

00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:01.550
who is a teacher in Virginia.

00:13:01.550 --> 00:13:04.270
And on his own once he
had his own children

00:13:04.270 --> 00:13:07.400
decided to reduce
homework substantially

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:09.950
to make homework the exception
rather than the rule.

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:12.290
And to eliminate most
quizzes and tests.

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:14.610
And what he found is that
students in his class

00:13:14.610 --> 00:13:16.580
did not become lazy
all of the sudden.

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:19.360
But, in fact, they
read more deeply.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:21.090
They thought more deeply.

00:13:21.090 --> 00:13:22.780
They wrote more creatively.

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:25.780
And so I think that thought
that Sir Ken Robinson

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:28.110
shares at the end of the
film applies to all of us.

00:13:28.110 --> 00:13:30.800
Whether you're a parent,
a teacher, or a student,

00:13:30.800 --> 00:13:33.510
we all need to be
advocates for change.

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:35.590
And so for anyone
here today, as well as

00:13:35.590 --> 00:13:37.470
the people that are
listening, I would also

00:13:37.470 --> 00:13:40.310
encourage you to get
this conversation started

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:41.460
in your community.

00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:44.650
We are looking to want
a national conversation

00:13:44.650 --> 00:13:48.820
about what's possible and about
the schools of the future.

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:51.090
And we've created a
lot of good resources

00:13:51.090 --> 00:13:54.470
to engage a community
to share the research

00:13:54.470 --> 00:13:58.640
behind these models that I think
are forward facing schools.

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:00.725
And better serve our
students and our teachers.

00:14:00.725 --> 00:14:03.990
So I would just say get
involved, start a conversation.

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:06.170
Form alliances with
like minded people.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:08.224
And create the change
that our kids need.

00:14:08.224 --> 00:14:10.390
JAMES: And if you haven't
watched Ken Robinson's TED

00:14:10.390 --> 00:14:12.690
talk on creativity it's
a must watch Google

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:13.690
and it's out on YouTube.

00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:16.630
So I want to invite
up Ken Dower.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:20.070
Ken is a Palo Alto Unified
School District board member.

00:14:20.070 --> 00:14:22.967
And he's a Google
staff engineer.

00:14:22.967 --> 00:14:25.050
I learned about Ken's
passion for education reform

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:27.960
from Vicki's book,
he was quoted.

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:30.475
He-- as I suspect
many of you know--

00:14:30.475 --> 00:14:32.675
Palo Alto school district
